         the function (\\ref{trans02}) have\n          continuous first-order partial derivatives satisfying the equations\n        \n\n[block_59] <p>: \n          throughout @@math:317:6aded8@@\n          Since the Cauchy-Riemann equations hold for @@math:318:0a1d75@@ and @@math:319:3b8cba@@ they also\n          hold for @@math:320:24047a@@ and @@math:321:c1a225@@ that is\n          @@math:322:1cff87@@\n          throughout @@math:323:0f64f4@@\n          Consequently, the function defined in (\\ref{trans02})\n          is differentiable. Furthermore, using the expressions in (\\ref{eqls})\n          and the Cauchy-Riemann equations we have\n          that\n        \n\n[block_60] <p>: \n          Hence, we have just proven the following:\n        \n\n[block_61] <p>: \n\n          The [[em]]Inverse Function Theorem[[/em]] states only the existence of a [[em]]local[[/em]]\n          inverse for @@math:333:71f25c@@ For example, consider the function @@math:334:e51c2d@@ defined\n          on @@math:335:784ba9@@ Then @@math:336:5e66f3@@ for every point of @@math:337:faef73@@\n          The [[em]]Inverse Function Theorem[[/em]] says that @@math:338:dcc1e7@@ has a unique local analytic inverse,\n          which is, in fact, some branch of the square root function @@math:339:6a72be@@\n          However, @@math:340:9e6dcc@@ is not one-to-one on all @@math:341:2da859@@ since @@math:342:e3d96a@@ Thus\n          @@math:343:8935d1@@ will be one-to-one only within sufficiently small neighborhoods surrounding\n          each point.\n        \n\n[block_62] <h2>: The Riemann Mapping Theorem\n\n[block_63] <p>: \n          In many applications it is common to look for a conformal\n          mapping of a domain @@math:344:289bf9@@ onto a simpler domain @@math:345:9e3613@@\n          A natural question to ask is whether such a mapping exists.\n          That is, given domain @@math:346:c245d4@@ and @@math:347:f24d67@@, does there exist a conformal\n          mapping of @@math:348:53c99a@@ onto @@math:349:418e62@@?\n        \n\n[block_64] <p>: \n          An answer to this question was given by Bernhard Riemann in 1851.\n          Although there was a gap in\n          Riemann's original proof (which was subsequently filled), this amazing\n          theorem still bears his name:\n        \n\n[block_65] <p>: \n          From this result we see that if @@math:355:e281f1@@ and @@math:356:df87a0@@ are any two simply connected domains,\n          with @@math:357:3bd1c8@@ @@math:358:d60c1f@@ then there exists a bijective conformal map @@math:359:839a06@@\n          If @@math:360:521490@@ and @@math:361:7a94f8@@ are conformal, we can set @@math:362:00fd78@@\n          (see Figure 10). Two domains @@math:363:b2eb56@@ and @@math:364:77855f@@ are called [[em]]conformally equivalent[[/em]]\n          if there is a bijective conformal map from @@math:365:b26ee0@@ to @@math:366:089d42@@ Thus the\n          [[em]]Riemann Mapping Theorem[[/em]] implies that two simple connected domains (unequal to @@math:367:5075f1@@)\n          are conformally equivalent.\n        \n\n[block_66] <figcaption>: \n            To transform @@math:368:8c2030@@ to @@math:369:52fc09@@ we compose @@math:370:4326eb@@ with @@math:371:7d1be0@@\n          \n\n[block_67] <p>: \n          Riemann's theorem is of critical theoretical importance, but its proof is\n          not constructive. This means that the theorem establishes the existence\n          of the mapping @@math:372:22dcf5@@ but it does not offer\n          a method to find a formula for @@math:373:68a9d8@@ A proof of\n          the [[em]]Riemann Mapping Theorem[[/em]] is beyond the scope of this text.\n          The interested reader can refer to \n          the books:\n        \n\n[block_68] <li>: \n            [[em]]Complex Analysis[[/em]]\n            by Lars V. Alfors, McGraw-Hill, 1979; and\n          \n\n[block_69] <li>: \n            [[em]]Basic Complex Analysis[[/em]]\n            by Jerrold. E. Marsden &amp; Michael J. 